</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=catafv>cataFV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Firemunchkin</span><br>  Posts: 173<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/24/02 9:07:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm57.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=184.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://users.bigpond.net.au/stbt/sigs/cataface.jpg height=60 width=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: SNOW!  /dance</span><hr size=1> I used to love it when the snow was about a foot or more deep, and then there was a bit of a melt and some freezing rain, which then froze again.  Making an icy crust on the surface of the snow, which meant I could actually walk on top of the snow without sinking into it, or leaving footprints.  (When I was a light kid, anyway.)<br>
<br>
A good freezing rain also means everybody doing the penguin walk downtown - sheer ice on everything!<br>
<br>
But there's nothing more magical than the first thick snow of the season.  When the flakes come down so thick and heavy that everything is muffled, the light is filtered into a sort of a mystical hazy grey you don't get at any other time, even traffic seems to sound distance and dampened.  It's quite warm, because the clouds are so thick they act as insulation, and there's no wind.  It's like you're wrapped up in a thick blanket, in a little world of your own, where the sights and sounds of the real world can't reach you.  Everything is so silent, so peaceful... it's an unreal world, I love that moment.<br>
<br>
